Investigating the Role of Islet Cytoarchitecture in Its
Oscillation Using a New b-Cell Cluster Model

Aparna Nittala, Soumitra Ghosh, Xujing Wang*

Max McGee National Research Center for Juvenile Diabetes, Human and Molecular Genetics Center, Medical College of Wisconsin, Children’s Research
Institute of the Children’s Hospital of Wisconsin, Milwaukee, Wisconsin, United States of America

The oscillatory insulin release is fundamental to normal glycemic control. The basis of the oscillation is the intercellular
coupling and bursting synchronization of b cells in each islet. The functional role of islet b cell mass organization with respect
to its oscillatory bursting is not well understood. This is of special interest in view of the recent finding of islet cytoarchitectural
differences between human and animal models. In this study we developed a new hexagonal closest packing (HCP) cell cluster
model. The model captures more accurately the real islet cell organization than the simple cubic packing (SCP) cluster that is
conventionally used. Using our new model we investigated the functional characteristics of b-cell clusters, including the
fraction of cells able to burst fb, the synchronization index l of the bursting b cells, the bursting period Tb, the plateau fraction
pf, and the amplitude of intracellular calcium oscillation [Ca]. We determined their dependence on cluster architectural
parameters including number of cells nb, number of inter-b cell couplings of each b cell nc, and the coupling strength gc. We
found that at low values of nb, nc and gc, the oscillation regularity improves with their increasing values. This functional gain
plateaus around their physiological values in real islets, at nb,100, nc,6 and gc,200 pS. In addition, normal b-cell clusters are
robust against significant perturbation to their architecture, including the presence of non-b cells or dead b cells. In clusters
with nb.,100, coordinated b-cell bursting can be maintained at up to 70% of b-cell loss, which is consistent with laboratory
and clinical findings of islets. Our results suggest that the bursting characteristics of a b-cell cluster depend quantitatively on
its architecture in a non-linear fashion. These findings are important to understand the islet bursting phenomenon and the
regulation of insulin secretion, under both physiological and pathological conditions.

Citation: Nittala A, Ghosh S, Wang X (2007) Investigating the Role of Islet Cytoarchitecture in Its Oscillation Using a New b-Cell Cluster Model. PLoS
ONE 2(10): e983. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0000983

