RESULTS
Development of the HCP b-cell cluster model
The HCP b-cell cluster The structural details of the HCP and
SCP lattices are given in the method section. To organize b cells in
a cluster, existing models till now utilized the SCP lattice, which
gives nc = 4 in 2D and nc = 6 in 3D. While examining the
architecture of
this protocol
significantly under-estimates nc. In addition, this does not give us
much room to investigate the functional consequence of
islet
architecture with varying nc values, or the consequence of non-
b cells or b-cell death. In this study we introduced the HCP lattice
to simulate b-cell clusters. This is based on the idea that a biological
cell can be approximated by a sphere, and spheres can be packed
more efficiently using HCP (the most compact packing for spheres)
than using SCP. In vitro experiments that studied clusters of b cells
also indicated that
lattice is a much better
approximation to the cluster structure [38,39]. With a HCP
cluster the number of intercellular couplings of each b cell is nc = 6
in 2D and nc = 12 in 3D. The arrangement of b cells in a HCP

the hexagonal

cluster and the setting up of their coupling terms

