Synchronization of bursting cells We first compared the
fraction of burster cells fb and their synchronization index l for all
SCP (SCP-8, -27, -64, -125, -216, and -343) and HCP (HCP-13,
-57, -153 and -323) clusters we have simulated, at different gap
junctional coupling strength from gc = 25 pS to gc = 1000 pS. We
find that at or above normal physiological conditions of gc,150–
250 pS [14,40,41], the SCP and HCP clusters did not differ much
and all cluster sizes exhibited a high fraction (.99%) of well
synchronized burster cells (l.0.95). Figure 2 presents the results at
gc = 200 pS. It is known that under pathological conditions, the
intercellular coupling can be significantly impaired. For example,
chronic hyperglycemia can reduce the gap junctional conductance
between cells [42–45]. A particular case, when gc reduces to 50 pS,
is also plotted in figure 2 for both cluster types. Over 99% of the
b cells in HCP clusters are still able to burst, while this number
dropped significantly in the SCP clusters with the smaller ones
affected the most. Additionally, the synchronization among the
burster cells is also significantly less in the SCP clusters, especially
the smaller SCP clusters.

Under pathological conditions including diabetes, loss of b-cell
mass usually occur [46]. It can be a mere loss at peripheral that
affects only the value of islet size nb. More often, the b-cell loss
occurs across the islet, which affects the values of both nb and nc.
We have compared the two cluster types with varying percentages
of b cells randomly removed from the cluster. In figure 3, we
present results at normal and impaired gap junctional coupling gc.
At normal coupling strength of gc = 200 pS (left column), both
SCP and HCP are fairly robust against loss of b cells. With up to
50% of b cells lost, over 90% of the remaining cells in the clusters
are still able to burst with significant synchronization of l.0.7.

A close look of the figure reveals that the HCP clusters are more
robust than SCP ones, especially when b-cell loss is over 50%.
This difference is more pronounced and can be observed sooner
when the gap junctional coupling is impaired. Specifically at
gc = 50 pS (figure 3, middle column), a HCP cluster can tolerate
more than 50% of b-cell loss, while 30% b-cell loss will completely
the bursting synchronization of an SCP cluster; at
disrupt
gc = 25 pS (figure 3, right column), even with 50% b-cell
loss,
the majority of remaining cells in the HCP clusters are still able to
burst synchronously, whilst the SCP clusters would not endure any
b-cell loss (with the exception of SCP-343, at #10% b-cell loss).
Other functional parameters We have also compared the
HCP and SCP clusters in terms of the other three functional
measures: bursting period Tb, plateau fraction pf, and calcium
amplitude [Ca]. We found that under normal conditions, HCP b-
cell clusters burst with significantly longer period (figure 4). This is
true even when the cell cluster is under significant perturbation,
with impaired intercellular coupling as low as gc = 50 pS and b-cell
damage up to 50%. When we examined pf and [Ca], we did not
see significant difference between the two types of clusters, either
at normal or under compromised cluster architectural parameter
values (data not shown).

