functional measures showed notable dependence on cluster size
nb. We then examined if
larger clusters have a functional
advantage when the intercellular coupling or functional b-cell
mass is compromised. We found that advantage of larger clusters is
only notable under extreme pathological conditions. In the same
figure, we also included results at gc = 50 pS, and when there is
70% loss of b cells (right column). Moderate functional gain with
increasing nb, primarily in terms of improved fb and l, is observed.

Results of the SCP clusters, also included in figure 5, indicate the
same conclusion.

The benefit of increasing nb is most notable for very small
clusters with nb,100. In the previous section where we compared
the SCP and HCP clusters, smaller clusters with less than 100
b cells
(SCP-8, SCP-64, HCP-13 and HCP-57) were also
simulated (figure 2). These results also indicated little dependence
on cluster size. Only when coupling is impaired, there is moderate
functional gain with increasing cluster size (dashed lines in figure 2).
Number of intercellular couplings per b cell nc As we
have pointed out earlier non-b cells in real human islets likely do
not couple or synchronize with b cells [23]. Their presence will
make the effective nc value less than the number of the nearest
neighbors each b cells has (as not all of them are b cells). 30% non-
b cells translates to an effective nc = 8.4 in our HCP model, and
50% non-b cells means nc = 6. Pathological loss of b-cell mass can
also lead to reduced nc. Therefore it is of interest to determine the
functional role of nc.

Intuitively one would expect that more intercellular coupling is
desirable for the heterogeneous b-cell population in order to
coordinate and synchronize their bursting and insulin release. We

