have found that this is indeed the case. Figure 6 gives the results of
the 5 bursting measures for a HCP-323 b-cell cluster at normal
and impaired coupling strength of gc = 200 pS and gc = 25 pS,
respectively. We have also included in the figure, results for
a cluster of totally uncoupled b cells (nc = 0 or gc = 0, dashed lines).
The results of the two synchronization measures, fb and l, are
particularly revealing. Under normal conditions each b-cell on
average needs to be coupled to at least 3 other b cells (nc.2.4), in
order to reach synchronized bursting of the cluster. The bursting
coordination improves with increasing value of nc. However, this
improvement plateaus at around nc = 6, a value that is about half
of its up-limit in a HCP cluster. The simulation results for other
clusters with more than 100 b cells (HCP-153 and SCP125, -216,
-343) are quantitatively similar (data not shown). Interestingly
the amount of b-cell couplings in a normal HCP b-cell cluster with
30–50% of non-b cells (as human islets do) is nc,6–8.4. This gives
the b-cell cluster some room to tolerate perturbation to its
architecture, namely, a small amount of random b-cell loss will not
lead to significant alteration of the cluster function. When the gap
junctional coupling is impaired, it takes much higher values of nc to
reach a good bursting synchronization among b cells. At gc = 25 pS,
a ,10 fold reduction from the normal strength, synchronized
bursting can only be achieved with nc.6. These results demonstrate
that a b-cell cluster with a higher-nc architecture will be more robust
against pathological perturbations.

