coupling

function [14,43,47].

strength gc The

intercellular
coupling strength is known to be a critical parameter for normal
islet
Impaired gap junctional coupling
between b cells will compromise their glucose sensitivity and
insulin release functionality [48,49]. We have simulated b-cell
clusters at varying coupling strength from 25 pS to 1000 pS. We
find that at low values below the normal physiological range of
increased gc generally leads to higher fb and l. Figure 7 presents
the results at both 30% and 50% of non-b cells. Evidently, the
functional gain in fb and l plateaus around ,200 pS.

The other three functional measures including Tb, pf and [Ca]
also showed dependence on gc, though the interpretation is less

obvious. The relationship is not always monotonic (figure 7).
Specifically, the calcium amplitude profile exhibited an initial rise
with increasing value of gc, it then peaked around a value within
the normal physiological range of gc and then drops afterwards.
This phenomenon has also been observed by others [14]. In general
there has not been enough study or a priori knowledge of these three
parameters to presume what values are functionally desirable. Of
interest is the fact that when gc is beyond the normal physiological
value range (gc.,250 pS), dependence on gc is much less marked
for all parameters and even diminishing for some.

Loss of b-cell mass During the disease progression for all
major forms of diabetes loss of b-cell mass has been observed [46].
The alteration sometimes could be merely a reduction in islet size
nb, but more often more profound changes
to the islet
cytoarchitecture occur. For example,
in type 1 diabetes the
infiltrating immune cells spread from peripheral islet vessels to the
centre of a given islet, causing b-cell apoptosis across the islet
[50,51]. In this situation both nb and nc are reduced, more
significantly so for nc. For this reason we have examined the
impact to the cluster bursting pattern when there is random b-cell
loss across the cluster. Both fb and l fall with increasing loss of
b cells (data not shown). The results are similar to that presented in
figure 3, where we compared the SCP and HCP cluster at 0% of
non-b cells. We are specifically interested in the threshold loss of b-
cell mass that would lead to functional failure. As the coordination
and synchronization of
is
fundamental to regulated, glucose dose-dependent insulin release,
we investigated this problem from the perspective of b-cell
bursting synchronization. We first simulated and determined the
degree of synchronization that would be expected by chance for
a cluster of uncoupled b cells. We then assumed that a b-cell
cluster would not be able to function normally if its l falls below 2
SD of this basal level. Using this criterion, we investigated the
threshold loss of b-cell mass that would result in functional failure,
under varying values of gc. Around physiological values of gc (150–
250 pS), at 30% non-b cells, we found that HCP b-cell clusters can
function with majority, up to 70%, of its b-cell mass lost. The

